revisions:
[{'created': '2014-05-12 08:54:40.000000000', 'message': 'Add functions for debian/ubuntu to enable services on startup

In ubuntu system, we can't find 'chkconfig' command, it
use "update-rc.d" or "sysv-rc-conf" for instead. Add
"sysvrc" option for ubuntu system to enable services
on startup.

example:
"services" : {
   "sysvrc" : {
      "mysql"    : { "enabled" : "true", "ensureRunning" : "true" },
      "apache2"  : { "enabled" : "true", "ensureRunning" : "true" }
   }
}

Change-Id: I5b7ceb7541e989f6b11fc1a5acf94275c1d2e75b
Closes-Bug: #1318481

commit_message:
Update sysvinit function to support ubuntu

In ubuntu system, we can't find 'chkconfig' command, it use
"update-rc.d" or "sysv-rc-conf" for instead.

_handle_sysv_command function will pick up the right command to
enable service for ubuntu or fedora or redhat, and also map systemd
to _handle_sysv_command and remove _handle_systemd_command.

Change-Id: I5b7ceb7541e989f6b11fc1a5acf94275c1d2e75b
Closes-Bug: #1318481

commit_message:
Consolidate eventlet code

This change consolidates eventlet code to a single module.
Importing eventlet drags along alot of other behavior changes
(such as replacing gettaddr with a version that doesn't support
IPv6), so it's safer if all the eventlet code is in one place so
it doesn't get imported when it's not needed, such as when
running under httpd.

blueprint extract-eventlet

Part of fix for bug 1178732

Change-Id: Ia557f8df7f856d7707a9d8c19800ddc36f1572ed

Firstly sorry for the turnover of patches, this touches a whole lot of files and there is a number of issues making sure that eventlet is being setup correctly that are best shown up by letting gerrit do a run. 

Also, the spelling isn't fixed for patch 12, we got there about the same time but i'll resubmit when jenkins returns. 

So regarding the test import order which make up the remainder of the comments. My intention is that calling use_eventlet twice (or stdlib) should be an error. This should only be called at the entry point to the program. The reason i've got it to just ignore being called twice is apache seems to reload scripts and fixing apache imports is a bigger issue. 

What i would ideally like to do regarding test ordering as i mention in the message is to have a single tests/__init__.py that would setup the environment for all the tests (note that having a tests/__init__.py has been killed in the past as well). This works for doing ./run_tests.sh however if you specify a test file to run (eg ./run_tests.sh test_catalog) then nose doesn't load it as a module, instead loading tests/test_catalog.py directly and so skips __init__.py. So hopefully once we go to testr or whatever is next this might go away and we can just use __init__.py.

By putting the environment.use_eventlet in test.py we satisfy the called once requirement, however it must be imported before anything else that imports environment. Annoyingly for alphabetic-ism keystone.auth imports cms which imports environment, so it essentially needs to be done before everything."}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2013-06-04 02:40:51.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 12: Works for me

commit_message:
Isolate eventlet code into environment.

The environment module will be configured once, during code initialization.
Subsequently all other possibly-evented modules will retrieve from
environment and transparently obtain either the eventlet or standard
library modules.

If eventlet, httplib, subprocess or other environment dependant module
is referenced outside of the environment module it should be considered
a bug.

The changes to tests are required to ensure that test is imported first
to setup the environment. Hopefully these can all be replaced with an
__init__.py in a post-nose keystone.

Implements: blueprint extract-eventlet
Change-Id: Icacd6f2ee0906ac5d303777c1f87a184f38283bf

commit_message:
Fix cinder Debian install procedure

This patch adds links to the "Respond to the prompts for" steps,
and removes the manual edition of cinder.conf for the
keystone_authtoken (as this is handled by Debconf).

This is a backport of: https://review.openstack.org/#/c/97158/

Change-Id: I4ef97b63dcd735077978ec26cea2acc6f8b36f82

commit_message:
Cleanup and gate on pep8 rules that are stricter in hacking 0.9

Fix up pep8 failures for rules we previously gated on, but that are now
stricter in there enforcement.

Ignore E251 due to https://github.com/jcrocholl/pep8/issues/301

Change-Id: I62b33e97c44c4a5be436b381cfbdaeb31cd2638b

commit_message:
Adds test for Floating Ips bulk Nova V2 API

This patch adds the test for following Nova V2 APIs-
- Create Floating Ips bulk
- Delete Floating Ips bulk
- List Floating Ips bulk

This patch also adds the config option for unallocated
Floating IP Range

Change-Id: I6af52bb2ce2caadf8491740097df71d041643e78

commit_message:
Default to PKIZ tokens

Changes the default token format to PKIZ from PKI.

Blueprint: compress-tokens

DocImpact  Changes the default Token Provider to PKIZ
           If only token_format=UUID is set, Keystone
           will not start with a warning about provider
           mismatch

Change-Id: Idf14ab6c6dd3a3cab42c35771416d9096ea4d900

commit_message:
Switch from unittest2 to oslotest(testtools)

This brings us inline with other projects and
allows us to use oslotest.BaseTestCase which
gets us stdout and logging on test failure.

Change-Id: Ic47e456d9076d6f2803a400eda9d6a89d0b30441

Correct the name that the client is installed as

pip needs to be able to find the library as "python-mistralclient"
not "mistralclient".

Change-Id: Ie2ea7fa1e464fd79c423e82013b08d575c5688c9

commit_message:
Load resources using Resource.load_all_from_stack()

Move responsbility for loading resource information back into the Resource
class. To maintain efficiency, load everything from the database at once in
the new load_all_from_stack() method. This allows us to remove the
_db_resources state from the Stack, collects the implementation in one
place and restores responsibility for its own DB state to the Resource
class.

Change-Id: Ia8059af57131e4b0a986c1f566b78aa935741a23

(4 comments)

Just a few questions inline'}, {'account_id': 2889, 'date': '2014-06-18 00:33:38.000000000', 'content': "Abandoned

After going around on this for a bit, I feel like my understanding of when we should (and should not) follow the specs process is improving.

And I don't feel like this is worth a spec any longer. Too much of the spec template is necessarily blank -- this isn't having any real impact on any APIs, on how to install or run Ironic, on service interactions, or changing any functionality. There's no upgrade or test requirements. Etc, etc...

If anything, it's nothing more than a bug that some of our log messages are being logged at the wrong level, and we're not following the standard well yet.

I'd like to thank everyone for the input and abandon this spec. I'd also still like Ironic's logging to be improved, but this has proven to be too heavy an approach for that.

Cheers,
Devananda"}, {'account_id': 10626, 'date': '2014-06-18 01:36:52.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6:

Agreed, specs seems like the wrong place for this.

I do think it would be worth documenting more Ironic-specific logging standards, but this spec largely addressed an outstanding bug.'}]

commit_message:
Standardize logging and improve log coverage

This blueprint will outline the appropriate log level to use for different
circumstances, and will be retained as a wiki page upon completion.

commit_message:
Add dhcrelay monitor via supervisor to restart

Dockerctl can start dhcrelay, but not ensure it
stays running. Supervisord can handle this task,
so it should watch the pid of dhcrelay and trigger
restart if it exits.

Change-Id: I75909d25418e625a2b154125e9a76e22c7443e47
Closes-Bug: #1324152

commit_message:
Update skip pep8 clause to use hacking

Now that projects don't directly use pep8 anymore but rather hacking,
update the ignore pep8 clause to say hacking.

Related patch to ignore hacking in the requirements sync check:
I114b05fb1ec99ec1e0e0162988edb5fa5517df46

Change-Id: Ib21646db18220b40db505856f4796c3d51228abc

commit_message:
SHA1 is not valid for CMS hashing

SHA1 is not a valid target for CMS hashing since it is being used
to obscure the tokens in the debug output of the keystoneclient
session object. This is to prevent a case where the debug output
could contain a valid token.

This change is to match with the Keystoneclient change:
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/99432/

Sample config has also been updated.

SecurityImpact

Change-Id: I774170ff1649bd3b55c6849ed07824bcddecea75

commit_message:
Bump hacking to 0.9.x series

Hacking 0.9.0 had a minor bug so require 0.9.1 or higher.

In order to keep this patch to just a requirements bump, ignore new and
stricter hacking rules that are being triggered. Fixing up the code and
turning these on is out of scope of this patch and is for future patches.

Change-Id: Iafbd4adae8c6b446d53b62dfc490eab8e76a43ac

commit_message:
Trivial refactors for gettextutils

* Favor one-line conditional assignments instead of more verbose
  assignments inside if...else clauses

* Favor the usage of generators instead of explicit for loops for
  perfomance

Change-Id: Idfbbec7cd2efa1ebbf5111abb24cb147edb176ee

commit_message:
Update the public API of the library

Move code around to hide parts that we want to protect, keeping the
public API exposed through the gettextutils and log modules. There
shouldn't be any changes to the code other than what is required to make
the moves work.

Change-Id: I135c535983b74a2e72d9ed133d3f3062752187ef

[{'created': '2014-06-04 20:59:17.000000000', 'message': 'Check the lazy flag at runtime

Update lazy flag handling to check it at runtime when each message is
translated, instead of once at startup when the translation function is
created. This allows a library to support lazy translation, without
requiring an application that uses the library to support it.

Change-Id: Iae22668119c8d0f5fb9c486436bfc35cdb88ac58
'}]
commit_message:
Check the lazy flag at runtime

Update lazy flag handling to check it at runtime when each message is
translated, instead of once at startup when the translation function is
created. This allows a library to support lazy translation, without
requiring an application that uses the library to support it.

Change-Id: Iae22668119c8d0f5fb9c486436bfc35cdb88ac58

Refactor resource initialisation from DB

Initialise the resource unconditionally to begin with, and use a separate
method to load data from the DB representation.

commit_message:
List stacks using Stack.load_all()

Abstract the code to list stacks in the database out of service.py and into
the Stack class itself.

Change-Id: If27a184ffc87067f708868f91aaf380753f2de3b

subject: Implement Stack loading from DB as a separate function

commit_message:
Implement Stack loading from DB as a separate function

Separate out the lookup of a stack in the DB from the actual creation from
an existing DB representation.

Change-Id: I709fb7c4059229371ba85a2cd6e87ec5361a5400

commit_message:
Update: Make addition/removal of resources more explicit

Use add_resource() and remove_resource() functions instead of indexing to
add and remove resources, to make it less surprising that the resources
themselves are being modified in the process.

Change-Id: I392cca8f68165988842affd1e23bce958645921b

subject: RPC API: Really don't include metadata in resource list

commit_message:
RPC API: Really don't include metadata in resource list

I made an attempt in e743158e7a61c00e2a32c340d3f268d0835f4c69 to not
include resource metadata when listing resources in the RPC API. Probably
due to a merge conflict, this was unsuccessful (although it did have the
effect of doubling the number of times we refreshed it from the database).

Neither the cfn API nor the native API passes on the metadata information
from list_stack_resources, so it is safe to remove this from the RPC API
for that call (which is the only one that passes detail=False) without
affecting the user-facing APIs.

Change-Id: Ibaddef9b290e88eb548c0427df5c007e3e14bc59

commit_message:
Do not create admin user if it exists already

In case if Keystone set to use some external authentication backend
(for example, LDAP), the admin user may already be pre-configured.
Need to avoid user creation in case if it exists already.

Change-Id: I6a23c424210c198a3dfc568db6d2ba21ddbf7bd5

commit_message:
Group Policy Mapping Model and Driver - Part 1

This patch introduces the resource extensions and mapping driver that
maps the Group Model to the existing Neutron resources.

Gerrit Spec: https://review.openstack.org/#/c/89469

Implements: blueprint group-based-policy-abstraction

Change-Id: Id0f23651cd87aa8605d16cb8cb1f022c848f4f17
Author:    Bob Kukura <kukura@noironetworks.com>
Author:    Sumit Naiksatam <sumitnaiksatam@gmail.com>
Author:    Mandeep Dhami <dhami@noironetworks.com>

subject: use real disk size to consider a resize down

commit_message:
use real disk size to consider a resize down

When resize an instance, we don't allow a resize down operation.
Currently, a flavor ephemeral size will be used to do the check,
but usually we might create ephemeral size less than flavor
ephemeral size. This patch use the real disk size to do the resize
instead of the flavor ephemeral size.

Closes-Bug: #1324005

Change-Id: I7e67ed8fbd87a06ea12cdbd39f3a93c145c904d7

commit_message:
Check the length of aggregate metadata

PostgreSQL gives an error if you try to shove 256+ characters
into a 255-character field. So we need raise a HTTPBadRequest
explanation if the length of aggregate_metadata.keys or
aggregate_metadata.values is above 255.

Change-Id: I2c778f2237ba5bd2aa8335a0eae80f3aad3e9157
Closes-Bug: #1219693

commit_message:
Add a single retry in to apt-get update

We are regularly seeing apt-get update fail in the gate, this may be due
to transient issues with the network/mirror. To work around this add a
single retry in.

Change-Id: I14b2ee69a5c39dacdb9c30c920cbd376f2d57831
Related-Bug: # 1286635

commit_message:
Generalize nova-specs to cover all Compute program repos

* Don't move nova to 'specs/nova' yet, as we have many outstanding patches
  and this will result in a large number of rebases. Instead
  'specs/nova/ will be created when there are fewer outstanding patches.
* add python-novaclient. Since this isn't part of the integrated release
  just target blueprints to trunk

Change-Id: I9073e05ea8aac078fcc7300be87cae717655aa39

commit_message:
Add test for HypervisorUnavailable on conductor

HypervisorUnavailable is added in excepted exception list in conductor
function migrate_server in commit d0a5e272, but the test cases are not added.
This patch adds test cases for it.

Change-Id: I83556e97cb151ff202b2377c00122a368b1c2892

Seems we're fixing the py3 compatibility issue, but we can't make the py33 gate pass. So I'm asking should we fix those py33 compatibility issue raised by Jenkins? And is there any way to just run the py33 check against just Marconi code(not checking other depended packages)? Thanks for working on this.

P.S. I'm glad to remove the -1 and +2 after my concern is addressed. Thanks."}, {'account_id': 6944, 'date': '2014-06-17 04:54:23.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

Fei,

Thanks for voicing your concerns. I'll try to address them below. :)

Natalia has been applying piecemeal fixes over the past month. The reason we can't fix them all in a single sweep is that often, a fix will unveil a new problem that some times depends on other openstack dependencies (say, jsonutils).

As of this moment, there is no way to run a check against marconi in isolation. The best we can do is to continue to monotonically decrease the amount of marconi that fails when run in a python 3 context.

Thanks again!"}, {'account_id': 10777, 'date': '2014-06-17 08:42:14.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

Thanks Fei for question and Alejandro for answer.

Yes,we selected interactive approach to adding support for py3k. The main criteria is that number of failing tests should be decreased (in some cases stay the same, since our gate is not checking mongo driver).

I just check that after fix, the number and failing tests on the gate is the same as locally, so patch is working as expected.'}, {'account_id': 8092, 'date': '2014-06-17 12:57:53.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Code-Review+1'}, {'account_id': 6484, 'date': '2014-06-17 21:43:01.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Code-Review+2 Workflow+1

commit_message:
Fix tests to be Python 3 compatible

This commit includes small fixes in the test suite, such as proper
integer division, dealing with difference in iterators.

Partially-implements: blueprint py3k-support
Change-Id: I4140258f564a639697a130a213d8a7733bee7713

commit_message:
Deduplicate status call checks

This commit updates the jsonschema validation method validate_response()
to use the rest client method expected_success() to check that the
correct status code response is received. Previously validate response
was doing the same check despite there already being a method available
for doing the check. As a part of using expected_success() to validate
the status codes using the jsonschema it was necessary to expand
expected_successs() to handle both single expected codes as well as a
list of codes. This is because it's perfectly valid for the jsonschema
to specify a list of expected responses.

Change-Id: I400bb9aff89c18f3964a1d8ec45bfb8dfd75301d

commit_message:
Fix /var/log/remote rotation template

- Put /var/log/remote rotation into an appropriate server role template
- Fix node names matching to exclude symlinks for IP addresses

Closes bug: #1329991
Closes bug: #1316957

Change-Id: Iacd96d6fa02b0c63c63ce5256cc832eda229dcc7
Signed-off-by: Bogdan Dobrelya <bdobrelia@mirantis.com>

commit_message:
Add oslo-incubator fixtures

We should use the available fixtures rather than doing mock ourselves.
There are also logging tests that could be improved with the logging
fixture.

Added individually as if you add the whole module then it also brings in
lockutils.

Change-Id: I548c5a5a76721c635feb5ce4e486edb5a59a429b

commit_message:
Reworked scenario tests to use their own non-default security groups

Moved _create_security_group_nova to base OfficialClientTest class, so
that now it can be used by all scenario tests. All scenario tests now
create security group with "loginable" rules explicitly and attach it to
servers instead of using "default" security group.

Change-Id: If82c681b4a7f62808f46b03c57d113f8f5c97f6f
Closes-Bug: #1247060

commit_message:
Respect $TMPDIR environment variable to run tests

On Fedora 20, /tmp now uses the tmpfs file system which means that all
files are stored in memory. Running Ceilometer tests write 1.2 GB in
/tmp.

This patch allows to set the TMPDIR environment variable to run tests in
a different temporary directoy. So I can use a directory on disk to not
use all my memory.

Change-Id: Ib87a988a4acb3cb568d3f3dda641f5a824f986da

commit_message:
GET messages on a non-existing queue returns a 404

In v1.0 we don't manage queues in a lazy manner,
so we have to return a 404 error code.

Change-Id: I1c2428b003b056cf51b73c95a4a4bbc085e9f52c
Closes-Bug: #1243752

commit_message:
Replace mknod() with chmod()

Using mknod() can be troublesome on Macs since the underlying system
call requires super-user privileges. Since its main use here
is to set the mode of the file (the subsequent call to open() is
enough to create it), we remove it and replace it with the less
troublesome chmod().

Partial-Bug: #1329077

Change-Id: I30c767792f44d27c6c0179474112015c5ab9bac3

commit_message:
Enforce a minimum time between all IPMI commands

This patch enforces the min_command_interval option, which was added in
the previous patch, to ensure that any given BMC is never "poked" more
frequently than this interval, regardless of the calling method.

Closes-Bug: #1320513

Change-Id: Id3849aadf3908133a92157b3e96dd752610533e9

commit_message:
Use .png instead of .gif images

This replaces the two image files used in the Admin Guide, "Introduction
to Ironic" page. The images were in .gif and are being replaced with
their .png counterparts, because .png is a better format.

Change-Id: Iec831d37f58f4e159b0cfc197bac5dad433d32cf

commit_message:
Add post Plan in YAML

the API now supports Post of plan in YAML format, so this patch updates
the client post method according to the api changes.

Change-Id: I6763ff3bb82625a56c86b5f2a5c71ade4dc76594
Related-Bug: #1309493

commit_message:
json default for transport and resource __repr__

Make json default for the transport and add a __repr__ method
for the resource which will be useful for some basic printing.

Change-Id: If006cbdaa5c50b948e118f3c8f5d5ab3c259905d

commit_message:
Move `location`'s domain code out of glance.store

This patch moves the location domain's specific code out of
glance.store. Since this code is Glance specific, it's necessary to move
it out of the store package so that we can then remove it all together
and use the `glance.store` library.

Partially-Implements blueprint: create-store-package

Change-Id: I7dc3d5d211054cabc2adc2b9b689cda11bce2190

commit_message:
Bump up to the six 1.7.x series

The six 1.7.x series brings in some nice adjustments
that users of six can take advantage of, including
but not limited to (the below were selected from
the six changelog and are widely used six features
across openstack):

- Select the implementations of dictionary iterator
  routines at import time for a 20% speed boost.
- Improve add_metaclass, so that it doesn't end up
  inserting another class into the hierarchy.

The full changelog can be found at:

https://bitbucket.org/gutworth/six/src/35f6/CHANGES?at=1.7.0

Change-Id: I80b09c5921ad277e1ec1da47ae718db8b43a8c23

commit_message:
Add missing docstrings and 1 unittest for LDAP utf-8 fixes

A minimal backport of these accepted master commits:

https://review.openstack.org/#/c/82396/
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/82398/
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/82399/

was done for Icehouse in the following:

https://review.openstack.org/#/c/91883/

In the above backport review it was requested docstrings be added for
some functions and an additional unittest be added. That work was done
for the Icehouse backport and was positively reviewed, at the same it
was requested the those changes be reflected back into master so as
not to lose them going forward. This patch does that, adds the
docstrings and one additional small unittest.

Change-Id: I881ba9b274692427d4c7b9f5357ee4735b4e6699
Related-Bug: #1172106

Added notifier entry points for backward compatibility

This is needed to support old values from incubator RPC layer when using
oslo.messaging.

blueprint oslo-messaging

commit_message:
Add configurable HTTP timeout to cinder API calls

Some Nova API calls require synchronous use of cinder.  (e.g. volume
list)  If the call to cinder lands on a slow performing or otherwise bad
cinder API node, the user of Nova API will see poor performance.

This patch adds the ability to control HTTP timeouts when calling the
cinder API.  By configuring a timeout, nova will be able to more quickly
retry its cinder request and hopefully land on a better performing
cinder API node.  This will help make the API response times more
predictable.

For backward compatibility, the default timeout value is None.

Closes-Bug: 1329797
DocImpact

Change-Id: I5cccced524d9a9d69ed41f755781d0b7ae3dc970

commit_message:
Add AllowedValues constraint to Rackspace::Cloud::LoadBalancer

The Rackspace Cloud Load Balancer service only allows certain
values for the algorithm property. This patch adds constraints
so that users get validation feedback prior to creating the
resource.

Closes-Bug: #1328654
Change-Id: Id24b426b1d3e49b09b3e468ea9e9675c05eaa160

commit_message:
Unbreak baremetal API tests that were not updated

A recent merge (88233) changed the baremetal test base to return (resp, body)
tuples from its create_* methods instead of the created objects.  This updates
the test cases that were missed in this patch and unbreaks all Ironic CI jobs
that were overlooked in that review.

Change-Id: I691e36d0678a15737614b7867a4c6778e714f299
Closes-bug: #1330834

commit_message:
Add $TOP_DIR to the path when calling tools' scripts

The missing reference to $TOP_DIR prevent us to run stack.sh from a different
directory.

Change-Id: Ie15b89734264789bef9a8efcfdbbf2cdb89c936e

commit_message:
Set default to false for nova v3_api config option

This commit switches the default value for the nova v3 api config
option from true to false. This changes the default behavior to not
run the Nova v3 API tests. This is because the v3 is still marked as
experimental and is able to change in a non-backwards compatible way
which will cause issues when running with branchless tempest.
Additionally, the nova team decided not to do a standalone v3 api so
at some point this will disappear and instead become v2.1 of the api
with microversions. When you couple this with the fact that tempest's
gate budget is basically exhausted (tests shouldn't take over an hour
to run in the gate) this should be defaulted off. For more discussion
see:

http://lists.openstack.org/pipermail/openstack-dev/2014-June/037370.html

Change-Id: I13dbc4b433a0f6defbeebce958b2e1cbcf64ba7a

commit_message:
capture cpu information when we setup_host

some very odd results are coming back from hpcloud 1.1, would like
an actual cpu dump as part of the run.

Change-Id: I4f387a4e6cdf8bbd9334d01fe262e36632b859ac

commit_message:
Add logging for NSX status sync cache

This patch simply adds some log statements with debug
severity for tracking events related to the NSX object
cache kept by the operational status synchronization
thread.

This will  be helpful when debugging error conditions.

Change-Id: Ieb7b44b1117048c126d275dea2b8503b85eaba04
Related-Bug: 1329560

commit_message:
Add unittests for remote client

Remote client is used in servers tests to provide some common operations into a
remote server. It's backended by the ssh class, which already has tests, so all
of its calls are mocked and due to that there are some 'useless' tests that are
pretty much checking response's format and checking if the ssh call didn't
change to avoid inconsistencies in the future.

Partially implements bp unit-tests

Change-Id: I5dabc170a557c81bb9b0605bf101719585d7c53b

commit_message:
Configure heat keystone client for SSL when keystone uses SSL

When SSL is enabled in Keystone, the path to the Keystone CA file
needs to be set in ca_file in the clients_keystone section.

commit_message:
devstack should put admin_tenant_id in tempest.conf file while setup

Some of the test cases in tempest related to quota use
admin_tenant_name, ideally it should use admin_tenant_id.
As tempest.conf file does not contains admin_tenant_id
it should also be updated. tempest.conf file is generated
by devstack while setup of openstack, changes should be made
in devstack so as to put admin_tenant_id in tempest conf file.

Change-Id: I62baf5b1e21ebf8d3b511624c54741015b304955
Closes-Bug: #1321624

commit_message:
Add basic echo_* functions for grenade

Grenade, and possibly other components, re-use parts of devstack
libraries.  This provides basic echo_* functions to avoid missing
commands in several libraries.

Change-Id: I972d6208055a8c4ca4c9bfd5383ad3c7159d5cbe

The flavors in nova and trove are exactly the same.  Since you need to provide a flavor to trove in order for it to create an instance for you, provisions have been made in the API to query the available nova flavors.  You will get exactly the same results running 'nova flavor-list' and 'trove flavor-list' with the only difference being the amount of information displayed.  The trove client will only display the info pertinent to itself (basically the name of the flavor and how much memory it has).

Enhanced Trove (database) flavor API tests

 - Added test to make sure trove flavors matched OS (nova) flavors
 - Added response status checks to existing tests

Partially implements: blueprint trove-tempest

[{'created': '2014-05-29 22:16:43.000000000', 'message': 'Use except x as y instead of except x, y

According to https://docs.python.org/3/howto/pyporting.html the
syntax changed in Python 3.x. The new syntax is usable with
Python >= 2.6 and should be preferred to be compatible with Python3.

Change-Id: If375a4de31d24ab343fb33160ecfbf4d1aaa79b7
'}]
commit_message:
Use except x as y instead of except x, y

According to https://docs.python.org/3/howto/pyporting.html the
syntax changed in Python 3.x. The new syntax is usable with
Python >= 2.6 and should be preferred to be compatible with Python3.

Change-Id: If375a4de31d24ab343fb33160ecfbf4d1aaa79b7

This patch allows posting a message for queue that does not exist, and creates the queue on the fly.
Listing messages from a non-existing queue gives an empty list of messages with a HTTP code of 200.
Claim behavior is left unchanged.

commit_message:
Implement Lazy Create Queue in v1.1 API

This patch allows:
1.Posting a message for queue that does not exist, and creates the queue on the fly
2.Listing messages, Stats from a non-existing queue which gives an empty
  list with a HTTP code of 200

Claim behavior is left unchanged.

Implements : blueprint api-v1.1-lazy-create-queues

Change-Id: Ie8e1b068d78561deaf01ca84e47e506d88422c1e

commit_message:
Cut the heat flavor

1024Mb memory is too much for single instance.
approximately 4 GiB memory used even without a booted VM.

The heat auto-scaling scenario needs to boot 3 VM
(currently disabled), if any other test running in parallel
and boots up a vm it would easily can cause OOM an
issue.

The heat-slow job can work with 128 MiB instance memory,
but this change reduces it just to 512 MiB (safer for the guest),
and enough to avoid OOM issues on the host,
and let us to heve more vm at the same time.

The m1.tiny flavor is not good because now it has a hard coded
1 GiB disk limit and the f20 image requires 2 GiB.
Setting the disk size to '0' -> automatically use the virtual size
of the image.

Using multiple cores does not really helps in boot time :(,
but it might cause higher host load. (More locking)
Reducing the core number to 1.

Change-Id: Ice7c1253d15e91fd1c02bc8c6809335aaebfff4a

commit_message:
Add Neutron benchmarks scenario for creating and listing routers

In this patch:
    * scenario NeutronNetworks.create_and_list_routers is added,
      which does the following:
        - creates networks, subnets, routers according to scenario file
        - adds routers interfaces to created subnets
        - lists routers
    * refactoring in NeutronNetworks class for PEP257
      and methods arguments
    * a piece of rafactoring in ResourceCleaner tests
    * classmethod NeutronScenario._generate_subnet_cidr is re-implemented
      for using netaddr.IPNetwork class
    * base implementation for class fakes.FakeNeutronClient
    * some improvements and refactoring for fakes

blueprint benchmark-scenarios-for-neutron

Change-Id: I6dbbe9e476cdf0f1fd4c7f1387e830b5a46e2aa6

@Alexei: I want to have a sql database for alarm definition and a mongodb for metering. I just don't want to use the mongo  just for query/set small and well defined object like alarm.

(And obviously don't want use mongodb for metering)

I must split the storage API layer to ensure the storage driver don't have implicit link between alarm definition and metering data."}, {'account_id': 7763, 'date': '2014-06-11 10:12:48.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

I understand what you are trying to do I just wonder "why":

>@Alexei: I want to have a sql database for alarm definition and a mongodb for metering. I just don't want to use the mongo just for query/set small and well defined object like alarm.

What is the benefit of having it separated? It's much harder in terms of deployment to setup and maintain 2 separate database backends (with HA, disaster recovery, etc.) It must be a good reason for doing it and "just for query/set small and well defined object like alarm." doesn't seem good enough for me.

Usually I would say that it's reasonable to have separate databases in application if it needs to have database transactions (which is not supported by mongodb) for billing or similar purpose. I don't think that such flexibility (and configuration complexity) is worth adding if there are no other reasons why it's needed.'}, {'account_id': 2813, 'date': '2014-06-17 12:18:16.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 2.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-06-17 12:18:19.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

commit_message:
Separate alarm storage models from other models

This change isolate storage models used for alarm into a separate file.

This a preparation work to have all alarms related storage API inside
the alarm namespace and then be able to have a different database for
alarming and metering.

Partial implements blueprint dedicated-alarm-database

Change-Id: Iab6b70c6a48301164016823bd0f8e9781ca21abd

commit_message:
Bump python-swiftclient version

https://review.openstack.org/#/c/69187/ introduced SSL certificate checking
in python-swiftclient (released as v2.0). This patch ensures that the version
of swiftclient used will verify SSL certificates correctly.

This patch also documents the `swift_store_auth_insecure` configuration
option for bypassing the cert verification

DocImpact
SecurityImpact

Change-Id: I20ddab5c3359071daf7505268c72331e4c786987

commit_message:
Add comment to explain vbm function

As a wrapper around VBoxManage, vbm is a core function of the host-side
scripts, but it lacks a comment explaining what it does and how it is
used.

This patch adds that comment.

Partial-Bug: 1312764
Implements: blueprint openstack-training-labs
Change-Id: If3a0a13dd2dc83f031569cf8fc7cd9c604435321

Some concerns about CI testing."}, {'account_id': 6873, 'date': '2014-04-17 01:12:21.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: (2 inline comments)

'}, {'account_id': 6873, 'date': '2014-04-17 01:14:04.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

@Zhu Zhu, could you comment on the comments around 3rd party CI with something like turbo-hipster for scale and performance testing but with DB2?  I'm assuming no one within IBM has ever looked at that but not sure."}, {'account_id': 612, 'date': '2014-04-17 01:51:09.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

I believe this new supported database backend should be documented somewhere - suggest updating the "Documentation Impact" section from "None".'}, {'account_id': 6873, 'date': '2014-04-17 03:05:44.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

Tom, fair point.  Looking at the install guides in community the RHEL/Fedora install guide says to use openstack-db to setup the database which uses MySQL, and doesn't mention anything about PostgreSQL so I don't think I'd have anything in the install guide about DB2.

There are database topics in the security guide, chapters 32-34, so there would be DB2 considerations there as well, I can add a note to the spec that those chapters would need to be updated.

http://docs.openstack.org/security-guide/content/

There is also a reference here I guess:

http://docs.openstack.org/training-guides/content/developer-getting-started.html

And here (this is a copy of the same line above):

http://docs.openstack.org/admin-guide-cloud/content/compute-service.html

And there is one line here:

http://docs.openstack.org/trunk/openstack-ops/content/cloud_controller_design.html

"SQL database (such as MySQL or PostgreSQL)"

I can link all of those in the spec, but am I missing something else?'}, {'account_id': 7069, 'date': '2014-04-17 04:33:48.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

(6 inline comments)

"}, {'account_id': 6873, 'date': '2014-04-17 13:29:27.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: (7 inline comments)

'}, {'account_id': 6873, 'date': '2014-04-17 14:33:36.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: (1 inline comment)

'}, {'account_id': 6873, 'date': '2014-04-18 01:31:58.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

Before updating the spec I'm looking for some consensus here on Joshua's idea about failing the 245 migration that deletes records where instance_uuid is NULL, I like that idea but want to get agreement before updating the spec in detail for that point.

Would also like to get some consensus on the requirement for unit tests given mysql/postgresql aren't run against unit tests in the check queue and 3rd party CI isn't run in the gate, and the migrations will be tested in the devstack setup in the 3rd party Tempest runs with DB2."}, {'account_id': 7069, 'date': '2014-04-18 07:32:47.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3: (6 inline comments)

The unit tests for mysql+postgres are, afaik, ran in the check queue as well as gate. They are run whenever the opportunistic db credentials exist (and you're running tox/unit tests) which should be on all jenkins slaves (ie test nodes).

I think running the unit tests will be important to you even if it means doing them as a 3rd party where you can't gate. For example, it'll still catch people adding migrations db2 can't support transactions on (that may be passed by tempest not touching the new tables)."}, {'account_id': 6873, 'date': '2014-04-18 13:49:53.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3: (5 inline comments)

Thanks Joshua.

I agree the testing is important all around for QA, we definitely want all of that testing because we carry this code internally right now and know the pain when someone adds a migration that doesn't work with DB2, but I'm also hoping to stagger those requirements a bit so we don't kill this for Juno, but I realize that's not up to me."}, {'account_id': 6873, 'date': '2014-04-18 15:21:25.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: (1 inline comment)

'}, {'account_id': 5441, 'date': '2014-04-18 22:03:21.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

(3 inline comments)

I like the idea of failing the migration(s) that delete fields where uuid/instance_uuid is None.  As much as operators might be warned it's possible that someone will have data inadvertently deleted.  It would be better to have them do it themselves so there can be no surprises.

I would like to see third party unit tests for DB2, since it's been pointed out that Tempest may not touch everything and the unit tests can provide more coverage.  But IMO it shouldn't be a requirement for introducing DB2 support, since we've set the precedent of using Tempest as the bar for now."}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-04-18 22:03:22.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: No score

Starting check jobs.
http://status.openstack.org/zuul/'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-04-18 22:04:14.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Works for me

Build succeeded.

- gate-nova-specs-python27 http://logs.openstack.org/96/87096/3/check/gate-nova-specs-python27/aefa7e3 : SUCCESS in 42s
- gate-nova-specs-docs http://docs-draft.openstack.org/96/87096/3/check/gate-nova-specs-docs/79a55c2/doc/build/html/ : SUCCESS in 51s
'}, {'account_id': 6873, 'date': '2014-04-19 12:43:25.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: (3 inline comments)

Thanks for more review, I plan on doing an update of the spec this weekend sometime.'}, {'account_id': 1501, 'date': '2014-04-20 18:08:09.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

I'm not sure I know this area well enough to vote at a technical level - but my big concern with an additional DB backend is whether it is going to be transparent enough that someone who can currently develop for MySQL will be able to still do whatever they do today without having to stand up and understand DB2 in some depth as well.  

If we allow this one in then it feels that we'd also have to support Oracle and any other DB vendor that comes along, and if end up with a wide range of DB drivers in Nova we could find it very hard to make progess on any changes that hit the DB layer.

We already see this to some extent when working across hypervisors, and introducing similar issues at the DB layer worries me.

I'm not saying it shouldn't be possible for someone so minded to write a DB2 driver as a plugin if they want to - I'm just not sure I want to see such a beast in Nova itself."}, {'account_id': 6873, 'date': '2014-04-20 18:31:18.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

@Phil, I understand the concern, but would recommend skimming over the patch that adds the support first, you'll see it's nothing really magical:

https://review.openstack.org/#/c/69047/

The only big issue is the problem with creating foreign keys over non-unique columns.

Any problems should be caught with 3rd party CI, which is the same with virt drivers."}, {'account_id': 6873, 'date': '2014-04-20 18:32:15.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: (1 inline comment)

'}, {'account_id': 1297, 'date': '2014-04-20 18:50:03.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: (1 inline comment)

'}, {'account_id': 6873, 'date': '2014-04-20 19:18:20.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: (1 inline comment)

'}, {'account_id': 6873, 'date': '2014-04-20 19:18:47.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 4.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-04-20 19:18:48.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

Starting check jobs.
http://status.openstack.org/zuul/'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-04-20 19:19:38.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Works for me

'}, {'account_id': 1501, 'date': '2014-04-20 20:43:15.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

(Carrying on my comments from patch set 3)

Hi Matt, I get that technically this may be a simple thing to do right now (the patch set you pointed me at if I understand it seems to be dealing with a non-null constraint issue in DB2), but I'm still concerned about what the impact will be here going forwards.  Third party CI is fine up to the point where some change fails for a reason that only an expert in that 3rd party software can understand - and then the change stalls until someone that is an expert in that turns up to help (assuming of course that they are willing to do that)

If this was adding support for an alternative opensource database I think I'd be more relaxed (well probably just as worried, but more open to the risks and impacts) - but unless I have this wrong it ties the DB layer in Nova to always be compatible with a specific commercial DB product - and its really not clear to me what specific existing problem it is we have in Nova that makes it compelling to do that.    

The DB is so much at the core of Nova that I just have this nagging feeling that at some point we're going to come up against something that we really want to do that can be implemented easily in MySQL and Postgresql and find we're blocked because it doesn't map onto DB2.

I'm all for companies being able to sell licenses for their products on the back of Openstack by providing extra value and drivers, and if there are specific DB changes that are needed that also make sense in general (like not making instance uuid nullable) then pushing those as distinct changes I don't have a problem with.

But what I read from the BP and the notes about adding DB2 into the documentation comes across as you wanting make DB2 the peer of all of the existing opensource databases supported in Openstack today (in effect the only commercial product as far as I can tell that would have that status) - which is I why I feel uneasy about the context here of making DB2 a supported backend and the impact of that going forwards."}, {'account_id': 1501, 'date': '2014-04-20 21:04:30.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4: No score

Moving to a zero for now (fence sitting) - I'd like to hear other's opinions on what I posted, but I'm not sure it's fair on reflection to block the BP on this just yet."}, {'account_id': 6873, 'date': '2014-04-20 21:15:57.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4:

@Phil, thanks for the input. I guess I don't see this as the first thing like this which if it doesn't work or people don't know how to develop against it could be broken, there are a lot of things in tree that aren't even tested, 3rd party or not (thinking the ceph/rbd image code in nova, several exotic backends in glance and cinder, etc). There is also a Tivoli Storage Manager backup driver in Cinder which would be relying on a commercial product. I'm not saying those are valid justifications for adding this to nova - nova definitely has higher standards in my opinion on what gets in and what level of testing and maintenance is required on what's kept in tree, that's apparent from the virt drivers.

My view is that (a) DB2 is not fundamentally different than MySQL or PostgreSQL, this isn't like saying we're trying to add nosql db support to nova, this is just supporting another sql-based relational database.  And (b) is that there is 3rd party CI backing it up and several people in the community that can help with issues if they arise *and* can't be figured out via public documentation. FWIW, if I hit a problem with a new migration that didn't work on postgresql but worked on mysql and db2, I don't think I'd have any easier a time getting that fixed as I would with the public docs and forums for DB2, even though postgresql is open source.

And finally, if there are blocking issues and there is no support and there is no maintenance, I see this getting ripped out just like anything else would."}, {'account_id': 7069, 'date': '2014-04-22 03:59:16.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

(3 inline comments)

Looking good, I like this proposal.

My -1 is for discussing some kind of tool to ease the pain for operators who have null uuid's somehow.

If the migration stops until the tables are tidied up, it will block further migrations and therefore block an operator from upgrading altogether before fixing the problem.

I'm not sure a tool to help clean up bad rows is the right solution, but it's something we should consider. Perhaps just good documentation is enough with an educated guess that it'd be low impact."}, {'account_id': 2271, 'date': '2014-04-24 18:36:52.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

(1 inline comment)

Add v3-api-schema blueprint

This patch adds blueprint v3-api-schema for creating API schema of
Nova v3 API.

commit_message:
Added missing core_plugins symbolic names

Some plugins miss short symbolic name in setup.cfg, specifically Nuage
and Metaplugin.

Change-Id: I0198ae98654bbdddf8f2ba8dd3b80d0d447d6341
Closes-Bug: 1324487

commit_message:
Node-specific VM configuration files

The three files in this changeset define for each node (controller,
network, compute) the networks it is attached to, the last octet
of its IP addresses, and any port forwardings from the host system
to the VM.

Partial-Bug: 1312764
Implements: blueprint openstack-training-labs
Change-Id: I3dece1457ba78cd5eb7f3a455705b510cac0abe8

@Jay Pipes, the requirement is as following:

OpenStack nova is using plug-in for resource scheduling, so there might be some cases that someone using external logic to select the best host for cold migration, then call nova api to do cold migration on the selected host.

I think that we should export enough APIs for those operations, such as create, live migration, cold migration etc.

commit_message:
Interface names for /etc/hosts

This file is appended to /etc/hosts in all nodes (osbash and
Vagrant).

It allows users, trainers, and the training-guides to use interface
names that indicate both VM and network (such as controller-mgmt).

Note that only the network node is connected to all networks.

Partial-Bug: 1312764
Implements: blueprint openstack-training-labs
Change-Id: If888537d91ec0ca9c47dc259e61bc438b7f76d05

commit_message:
Download Vagrant insecure private key if necessary

Rather than expecting the user to download the Vagrant insecure private
key and put it into the appropriate directory, the script downloads the
key if it's not already there.

This patch also adds a README.rst. It explains the purpose of the
directory which may also be used to cache the matching public key
(used inside the VMs).

Partial-Bug: 1312764
Implements: blueprint openstack-training-labs
Change-Id: If0ee801f6f581230304ad5899b381680bce9154e

privileges (once for each network created or modified). This change adds
code that allows create_hostnet to keep the elevated privileges while
configuring networks. That is, it prompts once rather than six times.

Implements: blueprint openstack-training-labs

'}]
commit_message:
wbatch: elevated privileges for create_hostnet

Currently, create_hostnet.bat asks no less than six times for elevated
privileges (once for each network created or modified). This change adds
code that allows create_hostnet to keep the elevated privileges while
configuring networks. That is, it prompts once rather than six times.

Partial-Bug: 1312764
Implements: blueprint openstack-training-labs
Change-Id: I30f9c158c674f1e308dc14d5e2efef184b6d464b

commit_message:
Add note: Ubuntu 12.04 cannot preseed over https

Ubuntu 12.04 LTS cannot load a preseed.cfg file over HTTPS. This patch
adds a warning for enterprising users who want to host their own preseed
files.

Partial-Bug: 1312764
Implements: blueprint openstack-training-labs
Change-Id: I08b74bc0a3edd2b0752c9257e13647f216919007

commit_message:
pkiz String conversion

When the PKIZ token provider signs a token, force conversion of the
token to a string as the keystone client cms code produces unicode.

Without this change, Keystone errors out when validating tokens.  It
was only visible in tempest tests.

bp: compress-tokens
Change-Id: Ic932240fbbe5bd9da6197b37cf86092bde510f40

commit_message:
Convert EC2 API to use nova objects

This blueprint covers updating EC2 API and related functions to use the
Nova object model for all database interaction, like implementation in
compute manager & nova-network now.

Change-Id: Ic00a6e2091115a31748f9b48fc46363f1bba925c
Implements: blueprint ec2-api-objects

commit_message:
Iterates swift response earlier to get the correct status

We must iterate the next middleware app until we get a response
before asking for the headers and status.

Closes-bug: #1326250

Change-Id: I8947bc88754db93e3ebe01ea864c4b489d1bd870

commit_message:
Use created security group in scenario server test

In the scenario server basic ops test a new security group is created.
However, this security group is not used in the subsequent booted VM.
This patch passes the new security group at the creation of the VM.

Change-Id: Icd87e4af2541e8c43dfee0b9f880ba7372d9b379
Related-Bug: #1330519

commit_message:
Add init_xxx_node.sh

This script sets the hostname and configures networking in the node VM.
It gets the hostname from its own file name (which is appropriately set
by vm_build_node when copying the file).

Partial-Bug: 1312764
Implements: blueprint openstack-training-labs
Change-Id: I9d0daad40462202c42ddd3a591f93b23d9512d53

Don't keep a copy of the run_tests.sh flag list here since it
inevitably will get out of sync with the real list.

No need to go into detail on how unit testing is set up, since we already have a wiki
on how to run tests that applies for all OpenStack projects. Keep

"}]
commit_message:
Shrink devref.unit_tests, since info is in wiki.

Don't keep a copy of the run_tests.sh flag list here since it
inevitably will get out of sync with the real list.

No need to go into detail on how unit testing is set up, since we already have a wiki
on how to run tests that applies for all OpenStack projects. Keep
section with tox examples since that is the most commonly used command.

Change-Id: Ia8eb059be164d9df3edfd69aedcebfd028da45ff
Related-Bug: 1219040

when testing on a deployment without the telemetry service:

commit_message:
Fix ceilometer client init when ceilometer is not installed

Prevent KeyValue exception during ceilometer client init
when testing on a deployment without the telemetry service:
keystone catalog not returning the "metering" endpoint.

Change-Id: Id96c536aa4f97a7a570ed082462a118f936d22d9
closes-bug: #1319341

commit_message:
Added policy target to policy runtime Event

Previously, a sequence of updates sent to the policy engine
must all apply to the same policy.

This change enables a sequence of updates for different
policies to be sent in a single call.

Change-Id: Id1ec89757f1a748061e836275f9e883121791bd0

commit_message:
Port forwarding only from localhost interface

The current code configures port forwarding to the VM from all host
interfaces.

Most users probably don't want to expose their unsecured VMs to their
local network (or worse).

This patch limits port forwarding to the host's 127.0.0.1 interface.

Partial-Bug: 1312764
Implements: blueprint openstack-training-labs
Change-Id: Ib28439c728691510ac710544564e92193e66bf52

commit_message:
Add VIF_VHOSTUSER

This is based on a new QEMU feature called vhost-user for connecting
to a user-space vswitch via a unix socket.

Change-Id: I552a55f27f1c8c4a676bbf8df03c8f13a23c3638

commit_message:
Check the network_info obj type before invoke wait function

When instance schedule to host and it isn't first time schedule,
the instance may already allocated network. And then the code
will return an NetworkInfo object, not an NetworkInfoAsyncWrapper.
The checking code only assume it is NetworkInfoAsyncWrapper object.

Change-Id: I987902fc47e509e4fd08f762d66b16c09eaf5008
Partial-Bug: #1326207

[{'created': '2014-06-12 10:05:18.000000000', 'message': 'Sync "Prevent races in opportunistic db test cases"

This sync change Id82090743e8b93f6c960de066fd05d8a2f9fb934 from
oslo-incubator

Opportunistic db test cases use openstack_citest database credentials
to create schemas on demand in tests. This actually can conflict with
existing migrations tests in Nova and possibly other projects which
drop and recreate openstack_citest database, so that if there was an
open connection to openstack_citest database in an opportunistic test
case, Nova migrations test would fail trying to drop the database.
The solution here is to use openstack_citest user credentials but not
connect to openstack_citest database when creating/dropping schemas:
for MySQL we can use an empty db name and for PostgreSQL the service
postgres database.

Change-Id: Idc62b24b6ae51ea14f10e39d7b14115e36069637
Closes-Bug: #1328997
'}, {'created': '2014-06-13 15:56:04.000000000', 'message': 'Sync "Prevent races in opportunistic db test cases"

This sync change Id82090743e8b93f6c960de066fd05d8a2f9fb934 from
oslo-incubator

Opportunistic db test cases create schemas on demand, so that each
test case which inherits the base test case class, will get its own
db schema (i. e. races between tests are not possible).

In order to do schema provisioning we have to connect to RDBMS server
first. So far we've been connecting to the openstack_citest database,
which is guaranteed to exist on CI nodes. It turns out, there are a
few test cases in Nova (maybe in other projects as well), that drop
and recreate the openstack_citest database. If they happen to do that
when the opportunistic db fixture is in the middle of provisioning a
schema, those tests will fail (as there is an open session to the
database and thus it can't be dropped).

This can be solved easily by changing the way we provision new
schemas in opportunistic db test cases as actually, we don't have to
connect to the openstack_citest database at all:

 - for MySQL we can use an empty db name to connect to MySQL server,
   but not to a particular database
 - PostgreSQL requires us to specify the database name. We can use
   the service postgres database here (PostgreSQL shell utils such
   as createdb, createuser, etc use it for the very same reason)

Closes-Bug: #1328997

Change-Id: Idc62b24b6ae51ea14f10e39d7b14115e36069637

commit_message:
Sync "Prevent races in opportunistic db test cases"

This sync change Id82090743e8b93f6c960de066fd05d8a2f9fb934 from
oslo-incubator

Opportunistic db test cases create schemas on demand, so that each
test case which inherits the base test case class, will get its own
db schema (i. e. races between tests are not possible).

In order to do schema provisioning we have to connect to RDBMS server
first. So far we've been connecting to the openstack_citest database,
which is guaranteed to exist on CI nodes. It turns out, there are a
few test cases in Nova (maybe in other projects as well), that drop
and recreate the openstack_citest database. If they happen to do that
when the opportunistic db fixture is in the middle of provisioning a
schema, those tests will fail (as there is an open session to the
database and thus it can't be dropped).

This can be solved easily by changing the way we provision new
schemas in opportunistic db test cases as actually, we don't have to
connect to the openstack_citest database at all:

 - for MySQL we can use an empty db name to connect to MySQL server,
   but not to a particular database
 - PostgreSQL requires us to specify the database name. We can use
   the service postgres database here (PostgreSQL shell utils such
   as createdb, createuser, etc use it for the very same reason)

Partial-Bug: #1328997

Change-Id: Idc62b24b6ae51ea14f10e39d7b14115e36069637

Invoke create_nova_conf_neutron from odl-compute post-install
only if nova is enabled.

commit_message:
Add flag to set nova v3 api for tempest

This commit adds a new env variable, TEMPEST_NOVA_API_V3 to set
whether the tempest api v3 tests are enabled.

Change-Id: If14deb80f271061e70fae6c3d13b210ac0dd9399

I prefer what Xing suggested, using a force flag. So what if it is (typically) an admin action? The api wont allow someone with insufficient privileges. To me it seems simpler and more intuitive for the CLI to have a --force option and the client library to just have a force kwarg.

commit_message:
Added force-delete api support

Added apis:
'force-delete' (share)
'snapshot-force-delete' (snapshot)

Difference from 'delete' API is in avoiding
check of share/snapshot status.

Partially implements: blueprint manila-client-enhancements

Change-Id: I97122c6566a246448ccabf401ad90b51c1d0d4a8

commit_message:
Added ability to dump/load all policies at once

Previously there was no way to load policies from disk
into the policy engine or to dump policies to disk.

This change adds the ability to do so.  Each Theory class
now has the following functions.
o  policy(): returns any policy statements the theory represents
o  contents(): returns any policy or data the theory represents
o  __str__(): prints the theory in a form that can be parsed.
Different subclasses of Theory differ in whether they print
policy() or contents().

The Runtime class includes functions for loading/dumping
a particular file into a particular theory and for loading/dumping
all policies into a directory where each policy corresponds
to a file with the same name.

Change-Id: Ie80be4047b3798194aa8fab5fbcf29f858534609

commit_message:
Use identity_uri instead of auth fragments

auth_token middleware now accepts a standard URL string as the parameter
identity_uri instead of specifying protocol etc individually. Change the
services over to use this.

Also changes over some other places in which the auth fragments are used
individually to the new variables and fixes up some misconfigurations of
auth_token.

identity_uri option was release in keystoneclient 0.8.0

Change-Id: Iac13bc3d08c524a6a0f39cdfbc1009e2f5c45c2a

commit_message:
Update icinga install script to enable icmp checks

This patchset updates the icinga-core installation script to
setup the check_icmp icinga plugin as setuid.

For some reason the package doesn't seem to do this so we need to
do that here.

I've also tidied up the set -eux and set -pipefail at the top of
the script.

Change-Id: I35f5e3ffcfcab5d93a7bf902ba12fc7d0afea691

Adding my thinking for context - the commit message almost raises more questions than it answers "in certain cases", "causes problems", etc.


The only time we skip ports (i.e. the only time when requested_networks is passed) is when a VM build fails part-way. This port-skipping code was introduced by Ie1516c299ce6d79faf2d5103a14d6d8931d3ede2

The network allocation happens async to the build - see _allocate_network_async() - but we wait for that async allocation to complete before cleaning up. See network_info.wait() in e.g. _build_resources()

allocate_for_instance() appears to be able to auto-allocate ports ... but we're only skipping ports that were specified in requested_networks, but not auto-allocated ports


The idea here is that a user has created a port for this new instance and we don't want to delete that port just because the VM build failed, especially in the case where we're going to reschedule that build. The port will be deleted when the VM is deleted normally, though?


In allocate_for_instance() we set device_id to the instance UUID, indicating the port is in use

So, this really is a special case - the VM build failed after we marked the port in use, we don't want to delete the port, but we do need to mark it as not in use any more



Bah ... I was going to +2a this, but I really think this kind of info is important to include in the commit message so people can understand it later. commit_message:
Network: ensure that ports are 'unset' when instance is deleted

Commit a141206e9dfd31955b9b31d9e5a7f73bbd8510ca ensured that user defined
ports were not deleted when an instance is deleted or rescheduled. The
problem with this commit is that it did not reset the 'device_id' and
'device_owner' of the port. This leads to port leakage and eventually a tenant
is unable to launch any instances as their port quota has exceeded the
allocated amount.

The solution is for the deallocation to reset the 'device_id' and the
'device_owner' of the port. This is allocated when the port is actually assigned
to an instance.

In the case of minesweeper (which runs on OpenStack), the tenant was leaking ports.
The root cause was that the user defined ports were assigned to a specific instance,
which was deleted, as a result of a failed reschedule (which is legitimate).

When an instance is deleted all artificats of that instance should be reset on the
port.

Change-Id: Ie1516c299ce6d79faf2d5103a14d6d8931d3ede2
Closes-bug: #1321381

commit_message:
Add check credentials to log message if rabbmitmq closes socket

If one has the credentials misconfigured for rabbitmq currently the following
error message is shown: "AMQP server on 10.0.0.23:5672 is unreachable:
Socket closed. Trying again in 1 seconds. " This is confusing because the
problem is the login creditentials are wrong but the server can be reached.

Since the rabbmitmq server allowed the initial connection and closed the
socket it's likely an authenication issue. This patch now logs: "AMQP server
10.0.0.23:5672 closed the connection. Check login credentials: Socket closed"
to hint the user that it could be a credential issue.

Change-Id: Iadff35d88a9cf704c1edd2d5036a113966db3ea3
Closes-bug: 1325750

commit_message:
Sort security group rules by protocol and port

When adding new rules to a security group, it is useful to have the
rules sorted consistently across page reloads. This patch ensures
that the rules are sorted by protocol first, then by port. It is still
possible to manually sort the table using the client side capabilities,
but by default the table is now sorted by protocol and port, server
side.

Change-Id: I36d29461a8437f5689425706a7faae3399c6bf23
Closes-bug: #1326132

commit_message:
Add an option to enable the nova v3 api tests

This commit adds a new env variable DEVSTACK_GATE_TEMPEST_NOVA_V3_API
used to enable the Nova v3 API tests in tempest. This depends on
devstack change: If14deb80f271061e70fae6c3d13b210ac0dd9399

Change-Id: I0e4fd5a1f1cde138af08f1cf9bf4b9e80c241e81

commit_message:
Bump hacking to 0.9.x series

Require at least 0.9.1 because 0.9.0. had a minor bug.

This change also fixes all found issues.

Rewrote some docstrings to fit H405.

Change-Id: Ifeef11b783dbe70b2652d2b9ea29d5b20f69f2ce

commit_message:
Check Env for exist before validating assignment

If we try to assign some role to some nodes with invalid cluster id:

    $ fuel --env 99 node set --role controller --node 1 2 3

we will get an internal server error (500). Since now, it's fixed.

Change-Id: I9bea9a498295b5db2114874c3502425d7dc94b46
Closes-Bug: #1317703

- 5_0 enums is not dropped by default

commit_message:
Add possibility to add several interfaces on 1 L2

Modified describe_environment, create_interfaces,
set_network methods so that they use bonding
parameters of settings.py module. Added new
parameters to settings.py that allow bonding.

Closes-Bug: #1301834

Change-Id: Ifd8f99596ce79f08d99bc99743a97df9884a4724

commit_message:
Fix high precision timestamps for UI logs matching

Fuel UI relies on the fixed timestamp pattern, so we have to
enable it back in syslog logging config.

Closes-bug: #1328877

Change-Id: Ib12779470f6bf91d26fbfa271c2af14e61535c54
Signed-off-by: Bogdan Dobrelya <bdobrelia@mirantis.com>

commit_message:
Clean up .gitignore

Several files were removed from the doc sources and config, so there are a
few folders in .gitignore, which are not needed anymore. Also there was a
build directory referenced and the only build directory is under the doc
folder, so this was corrected also.

Change-Id: I60f25d282caa813b3bfc790988578b9882ba95ab

commit_message:
Fix Sphinx directive name in session.py

In openstack/common/db/sqlalchemy/session.py a wrong directive name was
used for formattion code snippets. The directive '.. code::' was changed
to '.. code-block::' in oslo-incubator in this commit:
  I222a11d8a2101600e7cbb96f587515a32f697c2e
As this file now does not contain more formatting errors, it was removed
from the exclude list of Sphinx in conf.py.

Change-Id: I2fc7a8b8216d4bfc5232027f0beb11a036bf257c

commit_message:
Bump minimum oslo.config version to 1.2.1

oslo.config-1.2.1 has a required fix for interaction
with argparse, which effects trove and glance at least.
Related patch: I8d1b52e5390295726eb49af32eb7cab14c29592c

Change-Id: Icf7fa53834ddbd5a480984da9dbc39a207005b21

commit_message:
Fix whitespace that occurs after comma

Use a custom tuple of separators for json.dumps that avoids
having the comma+space, which looks bad if this is ever committed.
Replace it by just having ": " and "," (no space after) instead.

An example of this so that it can be more clear:

http://paste.openstack.org/show/84238/

Note the above paste where the old version has spaces after
commas where as the newer version does not have these spaces.

Change-Id: Ifd04d5e1b26ebdf9db374761f31baaf1e33d87cd

commit_message:
Fix lvm driver to be compatible with share manager

After last changes to share manager, LVM driver became incompatible.

Change-Id: I335afd8ba7f4d0e73c7f179290608b2b873651c7

commit_message:
Limit HAProxy exec check to primary controller

HAProxy IP is controlled by Pacemaker/Corosync. Exec fails on all Slave controllers.
This patch limits exec check to primary controller only.

Change-Id: Ic8daace980f2cb01feeb1f8006c9ca22d4a6a8f2
Closes-Bug: 1329780
Related-Bug: 1321662

[{'created': '2014-06-17 04:08:43.000000000', 'message': "Fix attaching/detaching problem in vm PAUSED state

When attaching/detaching device for vm in PAUSED state, device can not be
attached/detached properly. This's because libvirt take PAUSED state as an
active state, so the VIR_DOMAIN_AFFECT_LIVE flag should be added as a operation
flag when attaching/detaching device in PAUSED state.

Change-Id: I6132a0a28b8b44f784602c00565db27f385c4d89
Closes-Bug: #1330800
"}]
commit_message:
Fix attaching/detaching problem in vm PAUSED state

When attaching/detaching device for vm in PAUSED state, device can not be
attached/detached properly. This's because libvirt take PAUSED state as an
active state, so the VIR_DOMAIN_AFFECT_LIVE flag should be added as a operation
flag when attaching/detaching device in PAUSED state.

Change-Id: I6132a0a28b8b44f784602c00565db27f385c4d89
Closes-Bug: #1330800

commit_message:
Add path configuration file

This file is used by all scripts to find the directories for the files
they read or write. They find this file as "$TOP_DIR/config/paths".

Partial-Bug: 1312764
Implements: blueprint openstack-training-labs

Rewrited mox tests to mock (part 1)

Preffered module for unittests is mock,
so, this commit is intended to remove mox module
from manila's dependencies in modules:
manila/tests/api/v1/test_shares.py
manila/tests/test_service.py
manila/tests/test_share_api.py
manila/tests/test_share_lvm.py
manila/tests/test_utils.py

Partially implements: blueprint replace-mox-with-mock

commit_message:
Add osbash/Vagrant-specific configuration files

This changeset adds two configuration files, one for osbash and one for
Vagrant.

They contain the names of the VirtualBox shared folder and the
shell user. For osbash, there are some additional variables.

These config files could presumably be moved outside of the config
directory or disappear entirely, because there seems to be little
benefit in having these variables configurable.

Partial-Bug: 1312764
Implements: blueprint openstack-training-labs
Change-Id: Ieb0928debee463ef7211dae679ac38a6702ad084

[{'created': '2014-06-17 10:24:09.000000000', 'message': "Add and enable Vagrant script

This changeset adds vagrant/run_scripts.sh, a script executed by the
Vagrant shell provisioner inside the node VM.

run_scripts.sh executes the scripts enabled in:

config/scripts.nodeinit_vagrant
config/scripts.ubuntu
config/scripts.$HOSTNAME

Note that while Vagrant calls run_scripts.sh through symlinks named
after the nodes (controller.sh, network.sh, compute.sh), this has no
effect because run_scripts.sh relies on the hostname to select the
configuration.

The symlinks (and the Vagrantfile section that calls them) can be removed
once we are reasonably sure that we don't want to have node-specific
scripts for Vagrant on the host-side.

Partial-Bug: 1312764
Implements: blueprint openstack-training-labs
Change-Id: Ia5cfee0acddae26bd41e39b9185ed3d5990539f6
"}]
commit_message:
Add and enable Vagrant script

This changeset adds vagrant/run_scripts.sh, a script executed by the
Vagrant shell provisioner inside the node VM.

run_scripts.sh executes the scripts enabled in:

config/scripts.nodeinit_vagrant
config/scripts.ubuntu
config/scripts.$HOSTNAME

Note that while Vagrant calls run_scripts.sh through symlinks named
after the nodes (controller.sh, network.sh, compute.sh), this has no
effect because run_scripts.sh relies on the hostname to select the
configuration.

The symlinks (and the Vagrantfile section that calls them) can be removed
once we are reasonably sure that we don't want to have node-specific
scripts for Vagrant on the host-side.

Partial-Bug: 1312764
Implements: blueprint openstack-training-labs
Change-Id: Ia5cfee0acddae26bd41e39b9185ed3d5990539f6

commit_message:
Removed extra Murano OSTF tests

We have significant changes in Murano for Fuel 5.x versions
and we disabled all Windows-based OSTF tests for Murano,
new version of Murano doesn't required these tests, need
to clear the code.

Change-Id: I93368266d0ac2223d1e14958dbe199269a6d84a6
Closes-Bug: #1328855

commit_message:
Added force-delete action to admin actions

force-delete action will be available
for shares and snapshots with admin creds.

Partially implements: blueprint manila-client-enhancements

Change-Id: I896e8a83109879b96f0d7ef2ca2e52fcb7528bb3

commit_message:
Accept translated exceptions in exceptions.handle

If an exception with a translated message is thrown into
horizon.exceptions.handle, a UnicodeEncodeError is thrown in logging calls.

Also added in a test for this behavior.

Change-Id: I0bc71477d836daa0e27cdb10646b748fdc963f5d
Closes-Bug: 1284827

General query Don - when you talks about statsu updates are you including the service status in that (which is a liveness check and does need to be periodic) - or just resource status ?'}, {'account_id': 1981, 'date': '2014-06-13 16:24:57.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

My read of the current code is that it is reporting resource status and that is what I'm addressing here.

My `grand unified` view would be that the status info (which, even when it changes, is relatively static) is stored in the DB as it is currently.  Utilization based metrics that do change all the time and are more ephemeral should be reported directly to the scheduler but don't need the overhead of a DB update."}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-06-13 17:35:01.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Verified+1

commit_message:
Change compute updates from periodic to on demand

Currently, all compute nodes update status info in the DB on a periodic
basis (the period is currently 60 seconds). Given that the status of
the node only changes at specific points (manyline image
creation/destruction) this leads to significant DB overhead on a large
system. This BP changes the update mechanism to only update the DB when
a node state changes, specifically at node startup, instance creation
and instance destruction.

Change-Id: I9a53ba31619bab1b25d25b533beba8c86606637c
Implements: blueprint on-demand-compute-update

commit_message:
Fix messaging.get_transport caching

If some case get_transport can return a cached transport
even cache=False

This change fixes it and also adds some unit tests for this method

commit_message:
add a more comprehensive check-sanity

this ensures that all the services we believe are enabled in the
new environment are actually started after we have come up on the
new side. It does couple us to the devstack service list in a way
that we weren't before, however that's probably a long term useful
place to be.

This should make the discovery of failed started services a lot
more reliable.

Remove old `service_check` as that only failed if there was a
failure file, and not if the service never started up in bash.

Change-Id: I4fbafbcb8ac5c16ec79ded231e9a05b0ccbc04fc

commit_message:
Add xstatic and xstatic-jquery for Horizon

We are unbundling the static JS files from Horizon, moving them
to separate packages where possible. That means, that we have to
depend on those packages in requirements now.

This is for the patch https://review.openstack.org/#/c/82516/

Both xstatic and xstatic-jquery are not yet packaged in Ubuntu or
Fedora, but are used by at least one other large project, MoinMoin 2.

Change-Id: Iac5b5baf9d46c8deffd51d8b33345f7e21a50126
Partial-implements: blueprint https://blueprints.launchpad.net/horizon/+spec/remove-javascript-bundling

commit_message:
Switch to Hacking 0.8.x

This brings along Hacking requirements to match
other OpenStack projects. Since hacking already
requires the right pep8 pyflakes etc version,
those dependencies are not necessary to be specified
here.

Change-Id: Ifb575aa549bfd0288e44acda9a750ea40b9d14c2

commit_message:
Add timeout to all CLI tests

add existing cli.timeout option to all CLI tests. If the CLI ever takes
over 15 seconds (current cli.timout) then something is wrong.

Change-Id: Ifcd9bf4987c292d5518925352e1d2e1df3e579aa

commit_message:
CreateVM supports subnet specified

Currently the network info specified as part of server creation is limited
to network-id, port-id, and ip address.
When a network has multiple subnets then we need to also be able to specify a subnet-id.

Change-Id: I59cf7ee3c70694e14dfd42cdeba2cabddf2cab53
Implements: blueprint selecting-subnet-when-creating-vm

commit_message:
Sync kombu_reconnect_delay from Oslo

When reconnecting to a RabbitMQ cluster
with mirrored queues in use, the attempt to release the
connection can hang "indefinitely" somewhere deep down
in Kombu.  Blocking the thread for a bit prior to
release seems to kludge around the problem where it is
otherwise reproduceable.
The value 5.0 fits for low perfomance environments as well.

Cherry-picked from Oslo.messaging:
fcd51a67d18a9e947ae5f57eafa43ac756d1a5a8
Related-bug: #856764

Change-Id: I2d54b8c365ce7ed925652885104d999cecbe9fae
Signed-off-by: Bogdan Dobrelya <bdobrelia@mirantis.com>
